WE LOCATED THE DRUM AND OVERPACKED IT.  BECAUSE THE SPILL COVERED MOST OF THE TRAILER WE USED DISABSORBENT AND SPILL RAGS TO CLEAN IT UP AND PUT THAT MATERIAL IN ANOTHER OVERPACK DRUM AND SHIPPED IT OUT ON THE SAME MANIFEST FROM THE CUSTOMER ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND AT NO TIME DID THE MATERIAL COME IN CONTACT WITH THE GROUND.

ON 6-2-94, AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM, MONRACH DRIVER ED ROGOWSKI WAS DRIVING ON OLD COLMER ROAD, EAST SYRAUSE, NEW YORK, WHEN HE NOTICE DRIPPING COMING FROM HIS TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER INTO A PARKING LOT AREA.  HE INVESTIGATED THE LIQUID SPILL AND DETERMINED THAT IT WAS MURIATIC ACID AND MUST BE COMING FROM ONE OF THE TWO TOTES LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE BRANCH MANAGER WHO ACTIVATED EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURE.  THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE FROM VALVE FITTING OF THE TUFF TANK.

column168: MATERIAL WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO STORAGE AT THE CUSTOMER'S USING THEIR NITROGEN PRESSURE.  AS THE TRANSFER WAS STARTED IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT LEAK FROM A THREE INCH MALE FITTING ON OUR TRAILER.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND BEFORE THE CUSTOMER COULD CUT THE NITROGEN PRESSURE THE RESSURE RELIEF VALVE RELEASED AND PRODUCT WAS SPRAYED OUT.  THE FITTING WAS REPLACED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.  THE CUSMTOMER TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.

THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN LOADED AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION AND RETURNED TO OUR ALBANY TERMINAL FOR DISPATCH THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED TO START HIS TOUR OF DUTY HE DID HIS PRETRIP AND NOTICED A DRIP OF PRODUCT FROM THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER.  HE NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL MGR AND ALSO THE SHIPPER.  OUR PERSONNEL AND THE CUSTOMER PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  THE TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR PERSONNEL.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

DOCKHAND WAS PICKING UP SKID BEHIND DRUM WHEN FORKLIFT ROLLED FORWARD, SQUEEZING DRUM BETWEEN TWO SKIDS.  AFTER REAR SKID WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER, DRUM WAS TURNED OVER AND OIL DRY USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED PRODUCT.
DURING UNLOADING ONE BOX OF FIREWORKS (#42 AVEEN FIELDS) WAS DAMAGED CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF POWDER TO SPILL.  REST OF SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEM.

DRIVER TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON ROUTE 20 WAS STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 20 AND ROUTE 23 BY A VEHICLE EXPLAINING TO HIM THAT PRODUCT WAS SPILLING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  DRIVER STOPPED AND GOT OUT AND WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO FIND PRODUCT COMING OUT OF EXTERNAL VALVE ON TRAILER.  PRODUCT WAS SPILLED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 INCH THICK. DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE A COMPLETE INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER BEFORE LEAVING THE SHIPPER.

DRIVER HAD MADE DELIVERY OF BAGS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE TO SUPERIOR METAL PRODUCTS, APPARENTLY ONE OF THE BAGS WAS TORN AND SOME OF THE POWDER FELL ONTO A SKID OF CYCLE PARTS FOR ANDERSONS.  WHEN THE STOCK CLERK WAS HANDLING THESE PARTS SHE GOT SOME OF THE POWDER ON HER PANTS, WITH THE HUMIDITY IN THE AIR AND SWEATING IT CAUSED THE POWDER TO DISSOLVE HER PANTS AND SHOE, IT ALSO GAVE HER A SLIGHT BURN ON HER LEG.  O.H. MATERIALS OF FINDLAY, OHIO WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE RESIDUE.  FIRST AID WAS GIVEN TO THE CLERK WHO REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT.

TRAILER WAS LEAKING IN YARD, LEAKED OUT ABOUT A PINT, UPON INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND FLOOR OF TRAILER WAS WET FROM PRODUCT SPLASHING OUT WHEN TRAILER WAS MOVING BECAUSE THE BUNG HAD COME OUT ON THE TOP.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ATI COMPANY DRIVER HOOKED UP HIS DELIVERY FITTING AND HOSE TO THE SUPER TANK FROM HIS PETROLEUM PULL TRAILER.  AFTER VERIFYING THAT THE DELIVERY WOULD NOT EXCEED 95% OF THE TANK CAPACITY, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO BEGIN HIS DELIVERY.  AFTER OPENING THE INTERNAL AND THE QUARTER-TURN THE DRIVER VERIFIED THE PRODUCT WAS BEING DELIVERED INTO THE SUPER TANK WITHOUT ANY LEAKS OR  PROBLEMS.  THE DRIVER THEN TURNED AND WALKED TOWARD HIS TRUCK TO UNLOAD THE UNLEADED.  AS HE WAS PULLING OUT THE TRUCK DELIVERY HOSES HE TURNED TOWARD THE FILL AREA AND NOTICED THE SUPER FITTING HAD BECOME UNHOOKED AND GASOLINE WAS RUNNING OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER THEN SHUTT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM HIS TRAILER TO THE SUPER TANK, ASKED STATION MANAGER TO NOTIFY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND STARTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL OF GASOLINE WITH OUR COMPANY SPILL KIT.  AN INVESTIGATION AFTER INCIDENT LEADS US TO BELIEVE AN OVER FILL PROTECTION FLAPPER CLOSED PREMATURELY CAUSING BACK-PRESSURE WHICH JARRED THE DELIVERY HOSE & FITTING FROM ITS DELIVERY POSITION.  THE WASHINGTON STATE PATROL PERFORMED A UNIFORM VEHICLE INSPECTION TO OUR VEHICLE PRIOR TO IT BEING RELEASED FROM THE SCENE.  THE TRUCK WAS RELEASED FROM THE INCIDENT SITE WITHOUT CONTINGENIES TO CONTINUE BACK TO OUR TERMINAL FACILITY IN PASCO, WASHINGTON.  THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE PERMIT FOR THE SUPER TANK WAS SUSPENDED BY THE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY UNTIL THE AFOREMENTIONED ITEM WAS REPAIRED.  OUR TRUCK WAS EQUIPPED WITH ANOTHER SPILL RESPONSE KIT PRIOR TO BEING DISPATCHED FOR IT'S NEXT SHIFT.  IF THERE IS ANYTHING IN THIS REPORT THAT NEEDS CLARIFICATION PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CONTACT MONTE MOSS AT AMERICAN TRANSPORT.  PHONE 1-503-223-5400.

THE FOLLOWING IS A RECOUNT OF THE SPILL THAT OCCURED AT MCNEIL, MS, JUNE 16, 1994.  AT 08:50 CDT, 6-16-94, OUR DRIVER ADVISED BY TELEPHONE THAT HE WAS PARKED AT THE CITGO TRUCK STOP, MCNEIL, MS, EXIT 15 ON I-59 WITH LIQUID MATERIAL DRIPPING ONTO GROUND THROUGH TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SHIPMENT ON BOARD CONSISTED OF 8 DRUMS OF 6409 POUNDS OF WASTE POISONOUS LIQUID, N.O.S., 6.1, UN2810, PG1, RQ(DIAZON, PARTHION METHYL, SULFOTOP) EPA WASTE CODE P071.  THE SHIPMENT WAS MOVING FROM ENNIS, TX TO GREEN BRIER, TN WITH A STOPOFF AT MORGAN CITY, LA.  THE DRIVER PLACED SOME ABSORBANT MATERIAL ON THE GROUND TO CONTAIN THE DRIPPING MATERIAL .  AT 09:05 CDT, RIDEL-PETERSON ENVIRONMENT SERVICES, NEW ORLEANS, LA WAS CONTACTED TO DO THE REMEDIATION.  AT 09:13 CDT, THE TRUCK STOP MANAGER WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION.  AT 09:22 CDT, INITAL NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE MISSISSIPPI DEQ.  AT 09:37 CDT, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS ADVISED, REPORT NO. 244273.  DURING THE REMEDIATION WORK BY RIDEL-PETERSON, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 5 DRUMS WERE LEAKING DUE TO LOOSE LIDS AND/OR DEFECTIVE GASKETS.  THE DRUMS WERE ALSO DAMAGED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE LEAKAGE.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  ESTIMATED TOTAL LEAKAGE WAS 3 TO 5 GALLONS WITH ABOUT 1 GALLON LEAKING OUTSIDE THE TRAILER TOTAL COST FOR CLEAN-UP WERE $4524.26.  THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED AT ABOUT 18:00 CDT, AND SHIPMENT PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.

AN ADDITIONAL SAFETY-KLEEN TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST THE DRIVER IN OFF-LOADING THE TRUCK IN ORDER TO FIND THE LEAKING DRUM.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONDE CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO CALLED TO THE SCENE TO REMEDIATE ANY CONTAMINATED GRAVEL.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE BACK OF THE TRUCK WAS WIPED UP WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL THAT REACHED GRAVEL WAS DUG UP.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED, DRUMMED AND SHIPPED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  ONCE THE LEAKING DRUM WAS DETERMINED, IT WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED.

column168: DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, SWITCH CREW ADVISED YARDMASTER OF STRONG ODOR AND APPARENT SURFACE OF SPILL OF UNKNOWN PRODUCT AT THE WEST END OF TRACK 6, DELTA YARD, EVERETT, WASHINGTON.  INSPECTION OF SEVERAL TANK CARS ON TRACK 12 FOUND A GATX 11454 WITH EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT ON SIDES OF CAR. FURTHER INSPECTION BY HAZMAT RESPONDER FOUND MANWAY UNSECURED, WITH ALL LOCKING DOGS (8) OFF. AFTER SECURING THE MANWAY COVER, PLACARDS WERE REVERSED WAYBILL INFORMATION WAS CORRECT AND SHOWED THIS CAR AS A LOAD.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, WASHINGTON EPA WERE ALL NOTIFIED.  OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO HANDLE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS.  THEIR ASSESSMENT INDICATED LESS THAT 100 GALLONS SPILLED ON AREA APPROXIMATLEY 40 FEET BY 30 FEET.  EIGHT 55 GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED BALLAST WERE REMOVED AND THE REMAINING FOUND CONTAIMINANT WAS NEUTRALIZED, CLEAN UP COMPLETED AT 8:45 PM. column168: ON JUNE 13, 1994 THIRTEEN DUMP TRAILERS WERE LOADED AT FLORIDA WIRE WHILE IT WAS RAINING.  WHEN THESE TRUCKS ARRIVED AT LAIDLAW IN PINEWOOD, SC IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT WATER WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THEIR TAILGATES.  EACH TRAILER LEAKED FROM LESS THAN 2 OUNCES UP TO 1 GALLON OF WATER FOR A TOTAL OF ABOUT 5 GALLONS FROM ALL THIRTEEN LOADS.  THE LEAKING WATER WAS CAPTURED IN BUCKETS AND THE SOIL IN THE AREA WHERE THE LEAK OCCURRED WAS EXCAVATED AND DISPOSED OF AT THE PINEOOD LANDFILL.  IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT THIS TYPE LEAK FROM OCCURING IN THE FUTURE ROBBIE D WOOD WILL INSTRUCT ITS' DRIVERS NOT TO LOAD WET MATERIAL OR TO LOAD ANY TYPE MATERIAL WHILE IT IS RAINING.  ALSO, MORE ATTENTION WILL BE GIVEN TO THE TAILGATE SEALS AND LATCHES DURING PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE INSPECTIONS.

ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: ON JUNE 4TH.  A DRIP WAS DISCOVERED ORIGINATING FROM THE END GATE OF A LOADED TRAILER ON CLEAN-UP'S YARD.  THIS LOAD ORIGINATED IN SAVANNAH, GA AND WAS IN ROUTE TO HASKELL, OK.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO HAVE A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF OILY LIQUID INSIDE THE TRAILER.  A TRACK HOE HAD TO BE USED TO MOVE MATERIAL AWAY FROM THE END GATE SO THAT FLY ASH AND OIL DRY COULD BE PLACED TO ABSORB THE LIQUID. APPROXIMATELY 6 OZ. OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED THE TRAILER.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF SOIL FROM THE SPILL AREA WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INSIDE THE TRAILER WITH THE LOAD REMOVING ALL CONTAMINATION FROM THE GROUND.  THERE WAS NO OTHER CONTAMINATION OR THREAT TO OTHERS OR THE ENVIRONMENT.  NO MATERIAL WAS SPILLED NEAR ANY WATER WAY.  BECAUSE OF THIS DISCOVERY, I ORDERED AN INSPECTION OF OTHER LOADED TRAILERS, SOME FROM THE SAME LOCATION ON OUR YARD AWAITING DISPATCH.  THE INSPECTION REVEALED TWO OTHER TRAILERS WITH EXCESSIVE LIQUIDS IN THE LOAD.  THESE TRAILERS HAD NOT LEAKED.  THE TRACK HOE WAS AGAIN USED TO MOVE MATERIAL AWAY FROM THE END GATE IN ORDER TO PLACE FLY ASH AT THIS LOCATION TO PREVENT A LEAK FROM THE TRAILER. ALTHOUGH OUR TRAILERS, END GATES ARE EQUIPPED WITH RUBBER A GASKET, THESE TRAILERS ARE NOT DESIGNED TO CARRY FREE LIQUIDS.  MATERIAL MUST BE DRY OR VIBRATION DURING TRANSPORT WILL CAUSE LIQUIDS AND SOLIDS TO SEPARATE. EACH TRAILER WAS DELIVERED TO IT'S FINAL DESTINATION, CHIEF SUPPLY WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE GENERATOR WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED TO TAK CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURING AGAIN.  A FOLLOW UP LETTER ALONG WITH THIS REPORT WAS SENT (SEE ENCLOSED) TO THE GENERATOR CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT.

column168: DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE PRESSURE  RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF TRAILER AND PRODUCT OUT VALVE WHEN TRAILER WAS MOVED. OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED OUT TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP.

DOCKMAN WAS LOADING CYLINDER ONTO THE REAR OF TRAILER. HE HAD LAID THE CYLINDER DOWN AND WAS LOADING OTHER CYLINDERS WHEN HE NOTICED A GAS STREAM COMING FROM THE VALVE. ALL CYLINDERS ONLY CONTAINED RESIDUE OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN THIS SHIPMENT. BECAUSE OF THE VENTALATION ON THE DOCK, THE SMALL STREAM DISPERSED RAPIDLY. THE DOCKMAN WAS ABLE TO SHUT OFF THE VALVE, WHICH WAS PARTIALLY OPEN. THE BREVARD COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE LATER AND CHECKED THE DOCK AREA, CYLINDER AND THE DOCKMAN. EVERYTHING CHECKED OUT OK. THE CYLINDER WAS FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE AND THE DOCK AND DOCKMAN WERE NOT CONTAMINATED. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE IN THIS MATTER ON JUNE 21, THERE WAS A MEETING WITH THE EMPLOYEES OF THE TERMINAL TO COVER THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE AND THE HANDLING OF THE INCIDENT. A MEETING ALSO PLACE WITH THE SHIPPER TO COVER THE RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT AND PROCEDURES FOR FUTURE SHIPMENTS TO PREVENT ANY SIMILAR OCCURRANCES.

YARD CALLED CONSIGNEE AND CONSIGNEE RESPONDED; FOUND MANWAY HAD 5 BOLTS ONLY FINGER TIGHT AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS CUT.  THE CAR WAS ALSO SHELL FULL.  THE CONSIGNEE REPLACED THE GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

OUR DRIVER READ THE TANK TAPE AT 3 FT 1 IN.  HE LOOKED THE READING UP IN HIS TANK CHART BOOKLET WHICH INDICATED THAT HIS DELIVERY WOULD FIT.  THE DRIVER COULD NOT GET THE STORAGE TANK PUMP SYSTEM TO TURN ON SO HE USED THE TRUCK PUMP.  AFTER SWITCHING TO THE LAST COMPARTMENT OUR DRIVER SMELLED FUEL OIL SO HE SHUT EVERYTHING DOWN.  HE READ THE TANK TAPE WHICH NOW SHOWED THE TANK FILLED TO CAPACITY.  HE PUT THE BALANCE OF FUEL INTO ANOTHER TANK.  THERE WERE SEVERAL FACTORS CONTRIBUTING TO THE OVERFILL. IT WAS NIGHT WITH NO LIGHTING, THE ORIGINAL READING OF 3 FT 1 IN WAS ACTUALLY 30 FT 1 INC AND THE TANK PUMP SYSTEM WAS NOT USED.

column168: A GATEWAY WESTERN UTILITY TRAINMAN NOTICED A TANK CAR (GATX 35037) ON TRACK 29 AND A YARD, THAT WAS RECEIVED FROM THE A&S, APPEARED TO DRIPPING A FLUID FROM THE OUTLET CAP.  THE MECHANICAL SUPERINTENDENT PICKED UP A COPY OF THE WAYBILL AND CONFIRMED THE COMMODITY AS AMMONIUM FLOURIDE AND RETURNED TO THE SHOP FOR A BUCKET TO CATCH DRIPPING COMMODITY.  ENROUTE TO THE LEAKING CAR HE ALSO PICKED UP FIVE (5) LBS OF SAND TO ABSORB PRODUCT ON GROUND.  CARMEN ARRIVED AND AFTER CHECKING THE EMREGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE OF HAZARDS, THEY ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE OUTLET CAP.  THE OUTLET CAP CONTINUED TO LEAK APPROX. 90 DROPS PER MINUTE.  AT 11:32 CALLED CHEMTECH AND ADVISE OF THE PROBLEM.  AT 12:20 THE PLANT SUPERINTENDENT AND PRODUCTION SUPERVISOR, FROM CHEMTECH ARRIVED IN THE YARDS.  THE MECHANICAL SUPERINTENDENT ARRANGED TO HAVE CAR PLACED ON OLD PIG RAMP TRACK AND "BLUE FLAGED" TRACK.  AT 12:50 THE CHEMTECH EMPLOYEES ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN SHUT OFF VALVE AND TIGHTEN OUTLET CAP BUT CAR STILL LEAKED, THEY RETURNED TO CHEMTECH FOR ADDITIONAL EQUIPMENT.  THE GATEWAY MECHANICAL SUPT. RETURNED TO 29 TRACK IN 1-YARD AND PCKED UP THE SAND USED TO ABSORB THE COMMODTIY AND PLACED IT IN A COVERED CONTAINER.  THE CHEMTECH EMPLOYEES RETURNED AND AT 2:10 PM THE LEAK HAD BEEN REDUCED ENOUGH TO REMOVE THE OUTLET CAP.  ON REMOVAL OF THE OUTLET CAP THEY DETERMINED TO OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT LEAKING BUT THE OUTLET CAP WAS MISSING ITS GASKET.  A NEW GASKET WAS APPLIED AND LEAK STOPPED AT 2:35 PM.  CHEMTECH EMPLOYEES TOOK THE CONTAMINATED SAND AND LIQUID IN BUCKET FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 AM AN EMPLOYEE OF PACIFIC RAIL SERVICES, A LIFT CONTRACTOR FOR GATEWAY WESTERN, NOTICED A SLUDGE TYPE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM CONTAINER MATU 223159.  A CHECK OF THE WAYBILL IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, N.O.S., PLACARDED AS CLASS 9 WITH STCC 4875509. THE CONTAINER HELD 17 2YD NYLON AND PLASTIC BAGS, WHICH ARE D.O.T. EXEMPT AND HAVE NO DOT NUMBERS.  THE GATEWAY RAMP MANAGER NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE AT 9:00 AM OF THE LEAKING COMMODITY AND THE RESPONSE TEAM ARIVED AND VENICE RAMP APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM FOR INSPECTION.  THEY OPENED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THE LEAKING BAG OF SLUDGE WHICH APPEARS TO HAVE SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT RUPTURED.  THEY RETURNED TO VENICE APPROXIMATELY 2 PM.  THE LEAKING BAG WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINER ALONG WITH CONTAMINATED ABSORBANTS AND SOIL AND TAKEN TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY IN HANNIBAL, MISSOURI.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30PM A VOLVO TRUCK DRIVEN BY A CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A ONE-VEHICLE ACCIDENT ON THE ENTRANCE RAMP TO I-94, FROM CLINE AVENUE, IN HAMMOND, IN.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURED AS THE TRUCK WAS ENTERING THE ENTRANCE RAMP.  AT THE TIME THE ACCIDENT OCCURED, IT WAS RAINING.  THE DRIVER DOWNSHIFTED, HOWEVER, THE VEHICLE DID NOT RESPOND TO HIS STEERING EFFORTS AS HE ATTEMPTED TO MAKE THE RIGHT HAND CORNER OF THE ENTRANCE RAMP.  THE TRUCK SLID ON THE MIXTURE OF RAIN WATER AND OIL ON THE ROADWAY UNTIL THE FRONT WHEELS WERE COMPLETELY OFF THE ROADWAY.  WHEN THE TRUCK REACHED THE GRASS, IT REGAINED TRACTION AND BEGAN TO TURN TO THE RIGHT.  THE TRUCK CONTINUED APPROXIMATELY 40 FEET ON THE GRASS (PARALLEL TO THE ROADWAY), ON AN INCLINE.  THE VEHICLE THEN ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE, BECAUSE OF THE INCLINE.  THE ROOF OF THE TRUCK BECAME DETACHED AND APPROXIMATELY HALF THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK (80 MANIFESTED PIECES FROM AMERICAN STEEL FOUNDRIES AND ASSORTED SUPPLIES) WERE THROWN FROM THE VEHICLE.  THE INDIANA STATE POLICE AND THE HAMMOND INDIANA POLICE ARRIVED ON SITE TO SECURE THE AREA.  THE POLICE SUMMONED THE HAMMOND FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM AND OLDENBERG & SON, INC TOWING COMPANY.  THE DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION DELIVERED SAND TO BLOCK THE RUNOFF OF RAINWATER FROM THE SITE.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE APPROPRIATE CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL.  THE INITIAL CWM RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 PM AND THE ENTIRE TEAM WAS AT THE SITE BY 7:30 PM.  THE HAMMOND FIRE DEPARTMENT PULLED SAMPLES OF THE RUNOFF OF RAINWATER.  THE CWM RESPONSE TEAM PROCEEDED TO UPRIGHT AND INSPECT ALL OF THE CONTAINERS AND REMOVE THE REMAINING CONTAINERS FROM THE TRUCK.  DURING THIS INSPECTION, THE TEAM DISCOVERED 2 OPEN AND 5 LEAKING DRUMS.  ALL OF THE SPILLED OR LEAKED MATERIAL WAS ON THE ROADWAY OR IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. NO SPILL/LEAK MATERIALS REACHED THE SOIL.  THE TWO OPEN CONTAINERS CONTAINED LAB PACKS.  THE INVENTORIES WERE MATCHED TO THE DRUM CONTENTS AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO MATERIALS HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THE LIDS WERE PLACED BACK ON THESE DRUMS, AND SEALED PROPERLY.  THE FIVE LEAKING DRUMS CONTAINED PAINT-RELATED MATERIAL (ONE CONTAINED LATEX PAINT NOT SUBJECT TO THE HAZMAT REGULATIONS, FOUR CONTAINED CLASS 3 SOLVENT BASED PAINT WITH A HAZARDOUS WASTE CODE OF D001).  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF THE LATEX PAINT MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS (30 POUNDS) OF THE SOLVENT BASED PAINT MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  THE RQ FOR D001 WASTE MATERIAL IS 100 POUNDS, SO THERE WAS NO RQ AMOUNT RELEASED.  THE FIVE LEAKING CONTAINERS AND THE CLEANUP MATERIALS USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED MATERIAL WERE OVERPACKED INTO 16 GALLON DRUMS.  THE MANIFESTS WERE CORRECTED TO SHOW THE CHANGE IN DRUM SIZES.  ONE FIBER DRUM (WHICH CONTAINED WASTE BROMINE) BECAME SOAKED FROM THE RAIN, AND WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 16 GALLON DRUM.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THIS DRUM.  ALL OF THE WASTE WAS RELOADED INTO A SEPARATE CWM V
DISCOVERED LEAKAGE FROM A BOX.  OPENED THE BOX TO FIND A 5 GALLON PAIL PACKED IN STYROFOAM.  SEAM BROKE ON PAIL.  NO H/M MARKINGS ON BOX.
DRUM HAD CORROSIVE IN IT AND IT DEVELOPED A HOLE IN THE TOP SIDE OF IT. SPILL WAS RECOVERED BY RESENCY ABSORBANT.

DRIVER RECEIVED THE OK TO UNLOAD PRODUCT.  THIS PRODUCT WAS AIR UNLOADED AND AFTER APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES IT OVERFLOWED THROUGH THEIR VENT LINE INTO A CONTAINED AREA AROUND STORAGE TANK.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OF DISCHARGE VALVE AND NOTIFIED UNLOADING SUPERVISOR.  DRIVER HAD TO WAIT UNTIL THEY UNLOAD STORAGE TANK AND THEN UNLOADED BALANCE OF LOAD.  THE AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED AND WASHED DOWN INTO THEIR TREATMENT TANK.

UPON AUTHORIZATION FOR FURTHER TRANSIT THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO DUPONT IN TOLEDO, OH FOR OFFLOADING OF THE RUPTURED CONTAINER, AND ALL OTHER FREIGHT.  THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO COUSINS FOR CLEANING AND DUPONT MADE OTHER ARRANGEMENTS FOR CONTINUANCE OF THIS CARGO.

column168: WHILE OFF LOADING PALLET OF WASTE, PALLET COLLAPSED ON ONE SIDE, SENDING DRUMS TO THE GROUND.  STORM DRAINS WERE SECURED, BOOMS SET UP, ABSORBENT LAID DOWN.  CLEANUP BEGAN. column168: MERCHANDISE WAS RECEIVED AND SIGNED FOR FROM OVERNIGHT TRANSPORTATION COMPANY AT ABOUT 0800 ON JUNE 6, 1994.  AT 0830 WHEN PRODUCT WAS RELOCATED TO STAGING AREA, SIGNS OF LEAKAGE WERE NOTICED ON SIDE AND BOTTOM OF BOX. THE B/U EMERGENCY COORDINATOR WAS NOTIFIED, HAZWOPER TEAM WAS ASSEMBLED, AREA WAS EVACUATED AND CORDONED OFF, IGNITION SOURCES WERE EXTINGUISHED, AND WEARING LEVEL A PPE, CARTON WAS OPENED TO REVEAL 5 OF THE 8 BOTTLES COMPROMISED.  THE CAPS THOUGH STILL SCREWED ON AND SEALS IN PLACE, HAD THE TOP PORTION FO THE CAPS CRACKED AND MISSING PORTIONS, AS IF INTERNAL PRESSURE MIGHT HAVE CAUSED THE PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE MERCHANDISE WAS THEN PLACED INTO A PLASTIC LINED, DOT 17C, 8 GALLON DRUM WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL, CLOSED UP TIGHTLY, AND LABELED ACCORDINGLY, PENDING PICK-UP FROM OUR HAZARDOUS WASTE TRANSPORTER.  INDIVIDUAL WHO WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR RECEIVING MERCHANDISE WAS ADVISED TO PAY CLOSER ATTENTION WHEN SIGNING FOR ANY HAZARDOUS SHIPMENTS.  ADDITIONALLY A CORPORATE PRODUCT QUALITY REPORT WAS FILLED OUT AND FORWARDED TO OUR QUALITY AND REGUALTORY AFFAIRS DEPARTMENT SUGGESTING A PACKAGING IMPROVEMENT DISCUSSION WITH MALLINCKRODT.  HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST WILL FOLLOW SHORTLY.  OUR TRNASPORTER USUALLY FILLS IT OUT, AND I CHECK IT FOR ACCURACY.  WASTE SHOULD BE PICKED UP WITHIN THE NEXT WEEK AND THE MANIFEST WILL BE THEN FORWARDED TO YOU WITH AN ADDITIONAL COPY OF THIS INCIDENT REPORT.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A DRUM HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  THE DRUM WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE CARTON WAS LEAKING. THE CARTON WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  INSPECTION FOUND A PLASTIC JUG CRUSHED. column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHILE UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT, ONE OF THE THREE SKIDS FELL FROM THE TOP OF TWO OTHER SKIDS FROM ANOTHER SHIPMENT. THE DAMAGED SKID WAS STACKED UP TOO HIGH FOR ITS WEIGHT AND ON AN SURFACE THAT WAS UNEVEN. IT ALSO COULD NOT BE REACHED WITH THE FORKLIFT BECAUSE THE BOTTOM SHIPMENT WAS TOO LONG AND PREVENTED THE FORKLIFT FROM GETTING TO IT. WHEN THE DOCKMAN PULLED THE BOTTOM SKID BACK, THE SKID OF POISON FELL FORWARD. WHEN THE BAGS BROKE, THE UNLOADING CEASED AND THE TRAILER AND SPILL WAS SECURED. BETTER STACKING OR BLOCKING COULD HAVE PREVENTED IT.

DRIVER UNLOADED TWO DRUMS ONTO CUSTOMERS PALLET. AS CUSTOMER WAS TRANSPORTING THEM TO HIS WAREHOUSE THE TIRE OF HIS LIFT TRUCK WENT INTO A POT HOLE IN HIS DRIVEWAY. THE DRUM SLID OFF THE PALLET. WHEN IT HIT THE GROUND THE LID POPPED OFF. THERE WAS APPROX. 40 GALLONS SPILLED THE CUSTOMER DID THE CLEAN UP.

A FEEDER DRIVER WAS PULLING THE TRAILER OUT AT BAY 25A, WHEN HE MOVED THE TRUCK, THE PACKAGE FELL OFF THE BACK. HE SUMMONED A HAZ MAT CLERK WHO WITH THE HELP OF ANOTHER RESPONDER, IDENTIFIED THE PACKAGE, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, USED RESPONSE LIQUID DAMAGE. DAMAGE WAS PROCESSED ACCORDING TO DMP GUIDELINES.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE SORT AISLE. SORT NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR CLEARED THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND CONTACTED A 12 HOUR RESPONDER. PACKAGE WAS IDENTIFIED AND SPILL WAS CLEANED.
CRAIG KOFOD DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE. 12 FIRST RESPONDER DAVE FERRUGIA WAS NOTIFIED. DAVE AND I USED THE DECISION TREE FOR PROPER REMOVAL AND CLEAN-UP OF THE LEAKING HAZARDOUS PACKAGE.

THE SHIPPER FAX'D A COPY OF THE MSDS.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER CONFIRMED THAT THE FLASHPOINT IS 140 DEGREE. DURING A PREVIOUS CONVERSATION WITH MS. KEENAN, SHE ADVISED THAT THE FLASHPOINT WAS 150 DEGREE.  APPARENTLY THE SHIPPER CALLED FEDEX SPECIAL SERVICES, ADVISED THEY HAD A LIQUID WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 150 DEGREE.  WE TOLD THEM IT WAS A COMBUSTIBLE-NO ADDL PPWK WAS REQUIRED.

THIS FREIGHT CONSISTED OF TWO BOXES.  THEY WERE LOADED ON A PALLET FOR ANOTHER LOAD.  WHEN THE DRIVER MADE A DELIVERY, HE NOTICED ONE BOX HAD FALLEN ONTO THE FLOOR.  THE OTHER BOX REMAINED ON THE PALLET AND LOOKED SECURE.  HE DECIDED TO KEEP THE BOXES WHERE THEY WERE.  IN ROUTE TO ANOTHER DELIVERY, THE BOX FELL ON THE FLOOR AND PUNCTURED.  IT APPEARS THAT IT MUST HAVE LANDED ON ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT DURING THE FALL TO CAUSE THE PUNCTURE.  ALL OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX HAD LEAKED OUT, 2.5 GALLONS.  TO PREVENT THIS SIN THE FUTURE, PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES SHOULD BE USED.  THE DRIVER, SEEING THAT THIS WAS HAZARDOUS, SHOULD HAVE PLACED THE BOX ON THE FLOOR AFTER THE FIRST HAD FALLEN.

I RECEIVED A CALL AT MY HOME AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 A.M. ON THURSDAY JUNE 2, 1994 REGARDING A HAZARDOUS SPILL ON ONE OF OUR BALDWIN LINEHAUL UNITS. I WAS INFORMED THAT THE DRIVER WAS CARRYING (12) 55 GALLON DRUMS, AND 4 PORTABLE TANKS.  THIS WAS THE ONLY HAZARDOUS SHIPMENT.  (THERE WERE ONLY TWO BILLS, THE OTHER ONE WAS APPROXIMATELY 8000 # OF PAPER PRODUCTS.)  I WAS INFORMED THAT ALL OF THE DRUMS AND PORTABLE TANKS CONTAINED FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  I ADVISED MIKE ROTH (OPERATIONS MGR.) TO CALL CHEM-TREC, AND THEN TO CONTACT THE WISCONSIN STATE PATROL.  I ARRIVED AT THE N&M TRANSFER NEENAH TERMINAL AT 6:10 A.M. I WAS INFORMED BY THE PRESIDENT OF N&M TRANSFER, THROUGH THE DIRECTOR OF OPERATIONS, TO PROCEED TO THE SPILL SITE IN TOMAH.  WHILE ENROUTE, I ADVISED OUR TERMINAL PERSONNEL TO NOTIFY THE D.O.T. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER BY TELEPHONE.  THE INCIDENT NUMBER ASSIGNED WAS 241993.  SEVERAL ROADBLOCKS WERE SET UP BY THE WISCONSIN STATE PATROL.  THEY BEGAN THREE MILES EAST OF THE SPILL SITE.  HIGHWAY 21 WAS OPEN FOR LOCAL TRAFFIC ONLY, AND THE NORTHBOUND ON RAMP TO INTERSTATE 94 REMAINED CLOSED THROUGHOUT THE DAY.  I ARRIVED AT THE TOMAH COMMAND POST AT APPROXIMATELY 9:10 A.M.  PROCEDURES LISTED CHRONOLOGICALLY  10:30 I NOTIFY WASTE RESEARCH & RECLAMATION, EAU CLAIRE, WISCONSIN TO RESPOND TO THIS SPILL.  10:40 AM- COUNTY HAZ/MAT TEAM ENTERS TRAILER.  10:43 AM- AIR MONITORING INDICATED SAFE TO ENTER.  10:44- AM HAZ/MAT TEAM INDICATED LEAK WAS FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  10:50 AM- HAZ/MAT TEAM VERIFIES THAT LEAKING CONTAINER IS ONE SQUARE PORTABLE TANK, LOADED SECOND FROM THE REAR. HAZ/MAT TEAM DROPS BACK AGAIN OUT OF TRAILER BECAUSE OF AIR QUALITY. 11:23 AM- TOMAH POLICE OPEN UP HIGHWAY 21.  - NORTHBOUND ON RAMP TO INTERSTATE 94 REMAINS CLOSED.  12:05 PM- WASTE RESEARCH RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVES AT THE SPILL SITE 2:05 PM- FORKLIFT ARRIVES AT SITE.  2:22 PM- PALLET JACK ARRIVE AT SITE. 2:25 PM- FRONT END LOADER ARRIVES, BEGINS MOVING DIKED SAND FROM THE ON RAMP, AS INSTRUCTED BY THE MONROE COUNTY HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT.  2:30 PM- FORKLIFT BEGINS UNLOADING ALL CARGO FROM THE TRAILER ON TO ON RAMP.  2:38 PM - LEAKING TANK IS REMOVED, EXAMINED, AND PHOTOGRAPHED.  2:40 PM- DISCOVER RUPTURE TOOK PLACE AT WELDED SEAM LOCATED AT THE VERY BOTTOM SIDEWALL.  (SEE PHOTOS).  3:00 PM - ALL HAZ/MAT CONTAINERS HAVE BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER.  3:15 - 6:15 PM.  - ALL CARGO IS UNLOADED AND RELOADED.  TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH SPIL-SORB.  BOTTOM EXTERIOR OF TRAILER WAS WIPED CLEAN OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PRIATE EXCAVATING COMPANY REMOVED ALL SAND PUSHED OF ON RAMP ON TO COUNTY'S GRASSY AREA.  LEAKING CONTAINER IS PLACED ON REAR OF TRAILER.  (APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS OF INK ARE PUMPED OUT OF RUPTURED TANK AND PLACED IN TWO 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS.  6:35 PM- TOMAH POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT TRACTOR AND TRAILER FROM THE SPILL SITE.  RECOMMENDATIONS: CONCERNING THIS SPILL INCIDENT, SERIOUS CONSIDERATION MUST BE GIVEN TO THE FEDERAL REGULATIONS REGARDING TESTING AND RE-TESTING

ON 6/7/94 RAMP SUPERVISOR, TOM BALSER REPORTED AIRCRAFT 933AX HAD A STRONG ODOR ON THE MAIN CARGO DECK.  I, MICHAEL FRYE, HAZMAT COORDINATOR AND HAZMAT TECHNICIAN, ADDIE CAMPTON RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE I TOOK THE AIR MONITORING UNIT TO THE MAIN CARGO AREA OF THE AIRCRAFT. THERE WERE NO ABNORMAL READINGS DETECTED.  THERE WAS NO NOTICEABLE ODOR. ADDIE DONNED FIRE FIGHTING GEAR AND SELF-CONTAINED THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMITTING THE ODOR.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS MARKED "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. UN1210".  THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS PAPERWORK STATED THAT THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED INC, UN1210. TECHNICIAN CAMPTON OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND THERE WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ATTACHED.  THIS STATED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS "METHYL ETHYL KETONE, UN1193".  THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLE WAS A FIVE GALLON, FRICTION TYPE CONTAINER.  THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH ROOM FOR OUTAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AWAITING NEW HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS.

ON 6/9/94 HAZMAT TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN HANDED I, MICHAEL FRYE, HAZMAT COORDINATOR A FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS BOX WAS MARKED "FLAMMABLE" AND WAS MOIST ON TOP.  UPON INVESTIGATION I FOUND 30 PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WHICH CONTAINED A FUEL INJECTOR CLEANER.  THESE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES AHD SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. WITH NOT ENOUGH ROOM FOR OUTAGE, ONE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES.  ALSO CONTAINED IN THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE OTHER MISCELLANEOUS ACITO PRODUCTS, SOME OF THESE WERE AEROSOLS.  THERE WERE NO LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AWAITING PROPER CERTIFICATION FROM THE SHIPPER TO FORWARD ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION BY EXTENDED DRIVER, KYLE CORNELISON. THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY. I DRESSED IN FULL IN THE PPE AND ISOLATED THE PACKAGE. THE SOLUSORB WAS DISCARDED USING NORMAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

ON MONDAY JUNE 20, 1994 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:15 AM, AN ASHLAND DRIVER TOM HALL WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER 36 BAGS OF DICALITE SPEEDEX TO RAYTEX INC. LOCATED IN MARION SOUTH CAROLINA.  TOM HAD PARKED HIS TRUCK AT THE DOCK WHILE THE WAREHOUSER FOR RAYTEX INC. ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD ONE PALLET OF MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL WAS SHIPPED ON A SHORT 36" X 52" PALLET FURNISHED BY THE SUPPLIER.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO UNLOAD THE MATERIAL, THE EMPLOYEE FOR RAYTEX ENGAGED THE FORKS OF HIS FORKLIFT INTO THE SLOTS PROVIDED BY THE PALLET SPACING, PROCEEDING FORWARD INTO THE PALLET OPENING.  NOT REALIZED THE SHORT PALLET SIZE (LENGTH), THE FORKS EXTENDED OUT THE BACK SIDE OF THE PALLET AND INTO A DRUM OF ACETONE POSITIONED DIRECTLY BEHIND THE PALLET.  TOM HALL WAS ON THE DOCK OBSERVING THE WAREHOUSER UNLOAD.  HE NOTICED THE LEAKING DRUM AND IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE STOPPING THE LEAK.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE CONCRETE BELOW.  THE DRIVERS SPILL KIT AND OVERPACK WERE USED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL.  TOM HALL NOTIFIED SCOTT COLONNA WITH A BRIEFING OF THE INCIDENT AND ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS OF 20 GALLONS.  NO INJURIES RESULTED FROM THIS INCIDENT AND 1-800-ASHLAND WAS NOTIFIED SHORTLY THEREAFTER.

DOCKWORKER NOTED PAIL WHICH WAS SQUEEZED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOSS.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED PRIOR TO CLEANUP AND RECOVERY.

column168: ON 061594 AT APPROXIMATELY 450PM REEDER REVEIVED A CALL FROM MECHANICAL FOREMAN, TED HITT. HITT REPORTED THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. REEDER NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, DOW, HARRIMAN DISPATCH, AND THE HOUSTON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM. THE CAR HAD BEEN SHOVED AWAY FROM THE RIP SHED AND OTHER WORK AREAS. REEDER ORDERED THE AREA EVACUATED FOR A 500' RADIUS. THIS INCLUDED THE DIESEL SHOP. THE HOUSTON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM DISCOVERED THE LEAK WAS BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND THE NOZZLE. THEY WERE ABLE TO TIGHTEN 6 NUTS AND STOP THE LEAK. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 740PM. DOW PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND IT SAFE. THE CAR MOVED ON A SPECIAL TRAIN TO DOW FREEPORT ON 061694 FOR UNLOADING.

column168: REG MGR R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY YARDMASTER GARY JOHNSON ADVISING THAT SWITCH FOREMAN JOHN MCGILLAN REPORTED PRODUCT HAD SPLASHED FROM A TOP FITTING ON CAR FMLX 12216 WHEN IT WAS COUPLED.  INSPECTION BY MR. STINE DEVELOPED THAT THE CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A 9" QUICK FILL HOLE LOCATED ON COVER PLATE HAVING A LOCKING BAR ASSEMBLY.  THE FILL HOLE GASKET HAD BEEN DISLODGED.  NOTED THE WING NUT ON THE SWING BOLT WAS VERY TIGHT HOWEVER THE BOTTOM OF THE LOCKING BAR WAS TOUCHING THE SWING BOLT MOUNTING BRACKET WHICH WOULD NOT ALLOW THE COVER PLATE TO SEAT TIGHT.  THE "T" HANDLE WHICH IS ATTACHED TO THE FILL HOLE COVER PLATE AND THREADED THROUGH THE CENTER OF THE LOCKING BAR FROZEN AND TOTALLY SEIZED.  IT COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED TO LOWER THE COVER PLATE POSITION ON THE FILL HOLE NOZZLE, THUS NOT ALLOWING A  PROPER CLOSURE SEAL.  FRANGIBLE DISC FOUND TO BE INTACT, HOWEVER THE SAFETY CHAIN WAS NOT ATTACHED TO THE DISC RETAINER.  CONTACTED SUE MILLER AT FMC, LAWRENCE, KANSAS AND AFTER DISCUSSING THE INCIDENT SHE AGREED TO RESPOND WITH MR.TONY BOUCHER RETAINER. MR. TONY BOUCHER WITH A REPLACEMENT FILL HOLE LOCKING BAR ASSEMBLY.  THE ASSEMBLY WAS CHANGED OUT  AND A NEW "HYPLON" GASKET WAS APPLIED TO THE CLOSURE.  UPON COMPLETION  OF WORK SEAL UP X 140920 WAS APPLIED.   CONTACTED KANSAS CITY, MO. FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT 71 RESPONDED AND WASHED CAR.  UNIT UP1620 HAD A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE NOSE OF THE UNIT AND IT WAS ALSO WASHED.

column168: ON JUNE 27,1994 AT 1:45 AM, THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING EAST ON I90 AT 60 MPH IN THE RIGHT HAND LANE WHEN 4 HEAD OF ELK CAME FROM THE RIGHT HAND DITCH, OUT OF THE TREES ONTO THE ROAD IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK.  TRUCK MOVED TO LEFT LANE TO MISS THE ELK, APPLIED BRAKE, THE PUP UNIT 559A SWERVED TO EDGE OF ROAD, OVER THE EDGE OF ROAD INTO SOFT DIRT AND BROKE LOOSE FROM TRAILER UNIT 532.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL, COUNTY SHERIFF, MT HIGHWAY DEP, WRECKER, STEWART ANKRUM OF ANKRUM TRUCKING WAS CALLED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.  THIS HAPPENED AT MILE MARKER 32, 2 MILES EAST OF ST. REGIS, MT.  ED LEITCH WITH LMH ENVIROMENTAL OUT OF SACRAMENTO, CA (916)689-5287 TOOK CAR OF THE CLEANUP.
CARTONS WERE STACKED ON DOCK.  AT SOME POINT STACK WAS BUMPED KNOCKING THE TOP CARTON OFF.  ONE 1 GALLON BOTTLE SLIP ON THE HANDLE.  CONTENTS EVAPORATED BEFORE DAMAGE WAS DETECTED.

UNOCAL DRIVER, K. CAMPBELL, WAS MAKING A DELIVERY INTO CUSTOMER O.C. JONES AND SONS UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK OF DIESEL FUEL.  HE OVERFILLED THE UNDERGROUND TANK AND SOME PRODUCT WAS SPILLED AT THE FILL HOLE AREA AND CEMENT AREA AROUND IT.  SAND WAS DUMPED AROUND THE SPILL TO CONTAIN THE DIESEL.  THE CUSTOMER IS A CONSTRUCTION COMPANY SO EQUIPMENT AND SAND WAS READILY AVAILABLE.  THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARDOUS WASTE COMPANY AND WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED.  THE SPILL DID NOT LEAVE THE SITE.  THE SPILL WAS NOT A RESULT OF A VEHICLE TANK FAILURE.  THE SPILL WAS DUE TO THE DRIVER, DISCIPLINE ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURANCE CONSISTS OF RETRAINING OF THE DRIVER, DISCIPLINE AND A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT WITH OTHER DRIVERS AT THE NEXT SCHEDULE SAFETY MEEETING.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0100 HOURS ON 6/9/94, THE KCS CREW WAS INSTRUCTED AND MOVED TILX 260609 VIA AN INTRA-PLANT SWITCH ORDER AT THE PPG WEST LAKE, LA PLANT.  THE BLUE FLAG HAD BEEN TAKEN DOWN AND THE CAR WAS LISTED TO BE MOVED.  WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED IT WAS DISCOVERD THAT THE FILL APARATUS WAS STILL CONECTED. PPG PERSONNEL HANDLED THE SPILL RECOVERY AND CLEAN-UP. PPG REPORTED THE SPILL UNDER CERCLA TO THE NRC, REPORT #243062.  THE KCS DID NOT RECEIVE THE QUANTITY RELEASED UNTIL THE AFTERNOON OF 6/30/94.  THE KCS WAS UNABLE TO VERIFY THE QUANTITY RELEASED UNTIL THE AFTERNOON OF 7/1/94, AT WHICH TIME THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC UNDER DOT REG.'S 49 CFR 171.15(a) (4), REPORT #247146, RECEIVED BY PETTTY OFFICER BRIGHT.

SUNDAY AT 0755 HRS, AT THE NEW ORLEANS TERMINAL THE SEA-LAND CHALLENGER HAD A MINOR FUEL SPILL.  THE INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF A FAULTY GAUGE WHICH CAUSED APPROX. 10 BBLS, OF MFO  (MARINE FUEL OIL) TO ESCAPE FROM A "RISER" ON THE PORT SIDE OF THE VESSEL.  APPROX. 5 BBL WENT OVER THE SIDE ALTHOUGH REQUIRED TO CONTRACT A CLEANUP CREW BY THE COAST GUARD, THE CHIEF MATE (BILL BOYCE) AND CREW REACTED IN ENOUGH TIME TO LIMIT THE SPILL TO ONLY 10 BBLS TOTAL (GREAT JOB THESE GUYS ARE PROS!!!)  ALL APPROPRIATE PARTIES WERE INFORMED INCLUDING :  THE DEPT OF ENVIROMENTAL QUALITY, LA STATE POLICE (HAZMAT RESPONSE DIV), US COAST GUARD, RIEDELL-PETERSON HAZ RESPONSE TEAM.  ANY FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING SPILL IS ON FILE IN NEW ORLEANS.

column168: ONE JUNE 20,1994 JOHN DODSON WAS DISPATCHED TO PICK UP A LOADED TRAILER FROM J.B. HUNT SPECIAL COMMODITIES DROP YARD LOCATED AT HWY 90 & TAYLOR RD IN AMELIA, LA AND DELIVER TO MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS.  WHILE PERFORMING HIS PRETRIP INSPECTION MR. DOBSON DISCOVERED A DRIP ORIGINATING FROM THE END GATE OF THE TRAILER HE WAS HOOKING UP TO DELIVER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND.  NO MATERIAL WAS SPILLED INTO ANY WATERWAY.  MR. DOBSON FOLLOWED PROCEDURES IN HIS "DRIVERS DISCHARGE SHEET" AND CALLED IN AS REQUIRED.  I ADVISED HIM TO PLACE PLASTIC AND OIL DRY ON THE GROUN AND TO TRY AND TIGHTEN THE TURNBUCKLES WHICH WOULD INCREASE THE SEAL BETWEEN THE END GATE AND TRAILER TO STOP THE LEAK.  HE DID THIS AND WAS SUCCESSFUL IN PREVENTING ANY MORE MATERIAL FROM ESCAPING THE TRAILER.  MR. DOBSON REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL, PLASTIC SHEETING AND OIL DRY AND PLACED IT INSIDE THE TRAILER WITH THE LOAD.  ALL CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED.  I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED CHIEF SUPPLY OF THE SITUATION AND INQUIRED AS TO THE (RQ) OF ONE POUND (1 LB.), I MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND TO LOUISIANA HAMZAT UNIT.  I MADE THE REQUIRED NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 1839 HOURS FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT.  I  NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY HAZMAT UNIT AND ADVISED THEM OF THE SITUATION IMMEDIATELY AFTER NOTIFYING THE NRC.  MR. DOBSON UNLOADED THE TRAILER AT MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS THE FOLLOWING MORING WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  I HAVE HAD REPETITIVE CONVERSATIONS WITH CHIEF SUPPLY CONCERNING THE STATE OF MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED.  CHIEF HAS ADVISED THAT ADDITIONAL EFFORTS ARE BEING IMPLEMENTED TO CORRECT THIS SITUATION. DURING DISCUSSIONS WITH CHEIF SUPPLY'S PRESIDENT, STEVE MAJORS, HE INDICATED THAT CHEIF WILL USE LINERS THAT ARE MORE PUNCTURE RESISTANT AND A DIFFERENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL OR MORE OF THE CURRENT ABSORBENT.  THE SITUATION IS COMPOUNDED WHEN THE MATERIAL APPEARS SUITABLE FOR SHIPPING WHEN LOADED AND THEN LIQUIDS SEPARATE OUT DUE TO VIBRATION.  WE ARE IMPLEMENTING NEW INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS TYPE.  SEE ENCLOSED OFFICE NOTICE.

column168: ON JUNE 21, 1994, AN AGENT IN OUR CENTRAL LOST AND FOUND OPENED TWO FOOTLOCKERS THAT WERE LEFT UNCLAIMED IN OUR BAGGAGE OFFICE AT MIDWAY-CHICAGO OFFICE. MIDWAY HAD FORWARDED THE UNCLAIMED LOCKERS TO OUR CENTRAL LOST AND FOUND OFFICE IN ST. LOUIS, FOR IDENTIFICATION AND REFORWARDING IF POSSIBLE. UPON OPENING THESE FOOTLOCKERS, OUR AGENT DISCOVERED A 5-GALLON JERRY CAN IN EACH LOCKER, PROTECTED WITH 3 PLASTIC BAGS. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS NOTICED THAT EACH PLASTIC BAG CONTAINED WHAT APPEARED TO BE BABY POWDER, WHICH IN THE PAST HAS BEEN USED TO COVER THE SMELL OF DRUGS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1330/CST, THE D.E.A. WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED AT OUR FACILITY 15-20 MINUTES LATER. THE D.E.A. RAN A FIELD DRUG TEST ON THE LIQUID AND DETERMINED THAT THE CANS CONTAINED PCP. SUPERVISORS AT THE D.E.A. WERE NOTIFIED AND DUE TO PAST EXPERIENCE WITH THIS SUBSTANCE, CERTAIN PRECAUTIONS HAD TO BE TAKEN IN MOVING THE CANS. THE F.A.A. AND AIRPORT POLICE WERE THEN NOTIFIED BY THE D.E.A. AND TECHNICIANS WERE BROUGHT TO OUR OFFICE TO TAKE PICTURES OF THE EVIDENCE AND SAMPLES FOR ADDITIONAL TESTS. F.A.A. SPECIAL AGENT DON MUSCHLER, REQUESTED INFORMATION FROM THE BAGGAGE TAGS ON THE FOOTLOCKERS. TAG NUMBERS: TW615272 TW615273 IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THESE TAGS WERE ISSUED BY OUR SKY CAPS AT LOS ANGELES INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT. A LIST OF SKY CAPS SINCE, USED TO ISSUE THESE TAGS, WERE SECURED AND GIVEN TO F.A.A., D.E.A. AND AIRPORT POLICE.

column168: JUNE 22, 1994 - MATERIAL SHIPPED UNDER REFRIGERATION TO MAINTAIN ASSAY (40 DEGREES F). CONTAINER LOADED VESSEL KOELN EXPRESS IN NORFOLK ON 6/20/94 AT 2300 HOURS ENROUTE TO PORT ELIZABETH, N.J. ENROUTE, VESSEL NOTED TEMPERATURE DECLINE FROM SET TEMPERATURE OF 40 DEGREES F TO MINUS 4 DEGREES F. THE VESSEL WAS ADVISED TO DISCHARGE THE CONTAINER AT PORT ELIZABETH, N.J. TO DETERMINE IF THE FAILURE WAS SIMPLY A FAILURE OF THE TEMPERATURE RECORDING DEVICE OR THE ACTUAL CONTROLLING FAILURE OF THE REEFER AGGREGATE (I.E. WAS THE TEMPERATURE ACTUALLY MINUS 4 DEGREES F OR WAS THE RECORDING DEVICE DEFECTIVE). SHIPPER, BECTON DICKINSON (JOHN HORNIAK) WAS NOTIFIED. SHIPPER ADVISED IF THE TEMPERATURE WITHIN THE REEFER CONTAINER WAS BELOW FREEZING THAT THE CARGO COULD FREEZE AND AS SUCH MIGHT CAUSE THE INNER GLASS VIALS TO RUPTURE, BUT SUSPECTS THAT THEY HAVE NOT. BECTON ADVISED THAT THEY HAVE THE CAPABILITIES AND FACILITIES TO HANDLE SUCH PROBLEMS AND FURTHER ADVISED THAT THE CONTAINER SHOULD BE RETURNED TO THEM IN A FROZEN STATE (IF THERE WERE IN FACT ANY FAILURES, THE MATERIAL WOULD REMAIN IN A FROZEN STATE AND THEREBY NOT BREACH THE OUTER PACKAGING). 6/22-12.45 - NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER P.O. BRIGAT NOTIFIED OF "SUSPECTED" LEAK REPORT NO. 245452. WHILE ON THE PHONE WITH NRC, EPA REGION 11 NOTIFIED MS. GREEN. 13.00 - NOTIFIED NJ DEPE OPERATOR #2. column168: AT 22:00 HOURS ON JUNE, 1994 THIS OFFICE OF NATIONAL CARGO BUREAU, INC. WAS CONTACTED BY ANOUAR GUEMBRI OF HAPAG LLOYD CONCERNING A CONTAINER DISCHARGED FROM THE M/V ASTRO PROSPERITY AND WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. IT WAS REQUESTED THAN AN INSPECTION BE DONE TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE LEAKAGE AND THAT FINDINGS BE REPORTED BACK TO THE PRINCIPAL. UPON ARRIVAL AT YUSEN TERMINALS INC. 22:30 HOURS ON 28 JUNE, 1994, A MEETING TOOK PLACE WITH DON TREHUBA, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, AND SECURITY PERSONNEL. CONTAINER HLCU 457776-4, ACCORDING TO THE ATTACHED, "DANGEROUS CARGO MANIFEST," CONTAINED:  1) 24 PLASTIC DRUMS; AMMONIA SOLUTION, CLASS 8, CORROSIVE, UN#2672, 4800 KILOS NET WEIGHT.  2) 53 FIBERBOARD BOXES; AMMONIA SOLUTIONS, CLASS 8, CORROSIVE, UN#2672, 965 KILOS NET WEIGHT. 3) 1 METAL DRUM; HYDROFLOURIC ACID SOLUTION, CLASS 8, CORROSIVE AND POISON, UN#1790, 200 KILOS NET WEIGHT. TOGETHER WITH THE TERMINAL MANAGER AND TERMINAL SECURITY, THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED AT ROW 105-75. SECURITY REPORTED HAVING NOTICED THE LEAK EARLIER AND NOTIFIED TERMINAL OPERATIONS AS WELL AS THE HAPAG LLOYD REPRESENTATIVE. THE CONTAINER HAS CORROSIVE AND POISON PLACARDS APPLIED. IT WAS APPROACHED FROM UPWIND AND NOTICED TO BE DRIPPING MODERATELY AT THE DOORS AND THROUGH THE FLOOR BOARDS AT THE REAR. THERE APPEARED TO BE 5-10 GALLONS OF LIQUID ON THE GROUND AROUND THE CONTAINERS TAIL END. THERE WAS NOT A NOTICABLE ODOR EMITTING FROM THE LIQUID BUT SOME DISCOLORATION WAS OBSERVED ON A CONCRETE BUMPER UNDER ONE AREA OF LEAKAGE. THE Y.T.I. MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITH A SUPPLY OF SPEEDY-DRY ABSORBENT AND A DIKE WAS POURED AROUND THE SPILLED AREA TO CONTAIN THE PUDDLE. FOLLOWING DISCUSSIONS WITH ALL PARTIES CONCERNED AND DUE TO THE CONTINUED LEAKAGE, IT WAS DECIDED THAT A REPORT SHOULD BE MADE TO THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES REGARDING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENTS. ANOUAR GUEMBRI WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE SITUATION. IT WAS REQUESTED THAT THE UNDERSIGNED MAKE THE REPORT FROM TERMINAL, AND NOTIFY THE U.S. COAST GUARD AND LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT. AT 22:45 HOURS ON 28 JUNE, 1994, THE LOCAL OFFICE OF THE COAST GUARD WAS CONTACTED. MARINE SAFETY OFFICE DUTY OFFICER, TED FERRIS WAS TOLD OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER. HE TOOK THE REPORT AND INDICATED THAT HE WOULD CONTACT THE LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT. HE REFERRED US TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (800 424-8802) AND SAID TO CALL AND REPORT THE INCIDENT. AT 23:00 HOURS, 28 JUNE, 1994, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED AND A REPORT WAS MADE TO PETTY OFFICER ROBERTSON. REPORT #246582 WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS INCIDENT. AT 23:15 HOURS THE "OFFICER OF EMERGENCY SERVICES" WAS CONTACTED (800 852-7550) AND A REPORT WAS GIVEN TO MR. TOM FLYNN. HE ASSIGNED CASE #002899 TO THE INCIDENT. NO OTHER CALLS WERE MADE BY THE UNDERSIGNED AND THE THREE(3) ABOVE MENTIONED PHONE CALLS WERE MADE AT THE REQUEST OF HAPAG LLOYD. WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND U.S. COAST GUARD ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, ALL INFORMATION W

ON SATURDAY JUNE 11,1994, AT 1300 HOURS, THE FWEP-11 DERAILED 31 CARS AND 3 LOCOMOTIVES AT M.P.354/BAIRD SUBDIVISION, EASTLAND, TX. 5 RESIDUE NAPHTA CARS AND 2 HYDROCHLORIC ACID CARS WERE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INVOLVED. THE 5 NAPTHA CARS WERE INTACT AND DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT. THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS CONTAINED IN DOWX 7938 AND DOWX 7987. THE DOWX 7987 AND THE DOWX 7968 WERE TGE 12TH AND 13TH CARS, RESPECTIVELY. THE DOWX 7987 WAS AT A 3 O'CLOCK POSITION IN A NORTH/SOUTH DIRECTION JUST EAST OF A DRY STREAM AND THE MAINLINE TRESTLE. DOWX 7938 WAS ADJACENT TO IT (ON THE EAST) AT 6 O'CLOCK. A BOX CAR CAME TO REST ON TOP OF BOTH TANKS. THE DRY STREAM CONTAINED WATER AT THIS TIME BECAUSE OF RECENT HEAVY RAINS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER THE DERAILMENT HAPPENED AND CALLED IN EAGLE CONSTRUCTION TO BUILD CONTAINMENT DAMS IN THE DRY STREAM TO PREVENT CONTAMINATION OF THE DOWNSTREAM WATER SUPPLY. A TOTAL OF THREE DAMS WERE CONSTRUCTED AND THE ACID WAS CONFINED TO A 1/2 MILE OF STREAM BED IN APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILLION GALLONS OF WATER. NO DOWNSTREAM CONTAMINATION OCCURRED. THERE WAS AN ACID MIST RISING FROM THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID CARS. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET AND SR. SPECIAL AGENT/ HAZMAT CARL ZERWECK RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND CONFERRED WITH FIRE CHIEF PHILLIP ARTHUR ON THE INCIDENT AND VERIFIED THE MATERIALS INVOLVED. MS. ROQUET AND MR. ZERWECK SUITED UP AND DID A DAMAGE ASSESSMENT OF THE REGULATED - COMMODITY CARS WITH THE FIRE DEPT. RADIAN CORP. WAS ON SCENE TO PROVIDE AIR MONITORING. DOWX 7938 HAD LARGE DENTS, BUT THE TANK SHELL APPEARED INTACT. THIS CAR WAS UPSIDE DOWN AND THERE WAS BUBBLING ON THE GROUND AT THE NORTH END. WHEN THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS TORN OFF. THE OPENING LEFT BY THE VALVE WAS PLUGGED, TEMPORARILY SECURING THE CAR. REAGENT CHEMICAL, THE PRODUCT OWNER SUPPLIED TANK TRUCKS FOR OFFLOADING THIS PRODUCT WAS TRUCKED TO SAGINAW, TX. AND PUT INTO ANOTHER ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS 12,000 GALLONS. DOWX 7987 HAD LARGE TEARS IN THE TANK SHELL AND LOST MOST OF ITS CONTENTS DURING THE DERAILMENT. THIS WAS THE MAIN SOURCE OF THE ACID MIST. ONCE THE HEEL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DILUTED WITH AG LIME AND WATER, THE AIR CLEARED. ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS 19,000 GALLONS. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BENEATH THE TANK CARS AND THE SORROUNDING AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED TO A PH OF 6.9 AND 7.3 WITH AG LIME. APPROXIMATELY 353 TONS OF AG LIME WAS APPLIED TO THE ACID/WATER AND AGITATED. 1 SAMPLE WAS TAKEN NORTH OF THE TRACK AND 5 SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AT INTERVALS IN THE STREAM BED. A PH OF 7.1, 7.4, 6.9, 6.8, 6.3, AND 6.7 RESPECTIVELY WAS ACHIEVED. MIKE BURCH OF TNRCC APPROVED DAM REMOVAL WHEN TEST RESULTS VERIFIED NEUTRLIZATION.

ON SATURDAY JUNE 11,1994, AT 1300 HOURS, THE FWEP-11 DERAILED 31 CARS AND 3 LOCOMOTIVES AT M.P.354/BAIRD SUBDIVISION, EASTLAND, TX. 5 RESIDUE NAPHTA CARS AND 2 HYDROCHLORIC ACID CARS WERE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INVOLVED. THE 5 NAPTHA CARS WERE INTACT AND DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT. THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS CONTAINED IN DOWX 7938 AND DOWX 7987. THE DOWX 7987 AND THE DOWX 7968 WERE TGE 12TH AND 13TH CARS, RESPECTIVELY. THE DOWX 7987 WAS AT A 3 O'CLOCK POSITION IN A NORTH/SOUTH DIRECTION JUST EAST OF A DRY STREAM AND THE MAINLINE TRESTLE. DOWX 7938 WAS ADJACENT TO IT (ON THE EAST) AT 6 O'CLOCK. A BOX CAR CAME TO REST ON TOP OF BOTH TANKS. THE DRY STREAM CONTAINED WATER AT THIS TIME BECAUSE OF RECENT HEAVY RAINS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER THE DERAILMENT HAPPENED AND CALLED IN EAGLE CONSTRUCTION TO BUILD CONTAINMENT DAMS IN THE DRY STREAM TO PREVENT CONTAMINATION OF THE DOWNSTREAM WATER SUPPLY. A TOTAL OF THREE DAMS WERE CONSTRUCTED AND THE ACID WAS CONFINED TO A 1/2 MILE OF STREAM BED IN APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILLION GALLONS OF WATER. NO DOWNSTREAM CONTAMINATION OCCURRED. THERE WAS AN ACID MIST RISING FROM THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID CARS. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET AND SR. SPECIAL AGENT/ HAZMAT CARL ZERWECK RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND CONFERRED WITH FIRE CHIEF PHILLIP ARTHUR ON THE INCIDENT AND VERIFIED THE MATERIALS INVOLVED. MS. ROQUET AND MR. ZERWECK SUITED UP AND DID A DAMAGE ASSESSMENT OF THE REGULATED - COMMODITY CARS WITH THE FIRE DEPT. RADIAN CORP. WAS ON SCENE TO PROVIDE AIR MONITORING. DOWX 7938 HAD LARGE DENTS, BUT THE TANK SHELL APPEARED INTACT. THIS CAR WAS UPSIDE DOWN AND THERE WAS BUBBLING ON THE GROUND AT THE NORTH END. WHEN THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS TORN OFF. THE OPENING LEFT BY THE VALVE WAS PLUGGED, TEMPORARILY SECURING THE CAR. REAGENT CHEMICAL, THE PRODUCT OWNER SUPPLIED TANK TRUCKS FOR OFFLOADING THIS PRODUCT WAS TRUCKED TO SAGINAW, TX. AND PUT INTO ANOTHER ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS 12,000 GALLONS. DOWX 7987 HAD LARGE TEARS IN THE TANK SHELL AND LOST MOST OF ITS CONTENTS DURING THE DERAILMENT. THIS WAS THE MAIN SOURCE OF THE ACID MIST. ONCE THE HEEL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DILUTED WITH AG LIME AND WATER, THE AIR CLEARED. ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS 19,000 GALLONS. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BENEATH THE TANK CARS AND THE SORROUNDING AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED TO A PH OF 6.9 AND 7.3 WITH AG LIME. APPROXIMATELY 353 TONS OF AG LIME WAS APPLIED TO THE ACID/WATER AND AGITATED. 1 SAMPLE WAS TAKEN NORTH OF THE TRACK AND 5 SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AT INTERVALS IN THE STREAM BED. A PH OF 7.1, 7.4, 6.9, 6.8, 6.3, AND 6.7 RESPECTIVELY WAS ACHIEVED. MIKE BURCH OF TNRCC APPROVED DAM REMOVAL WHEN TEST RESULTS VERIFIED NEUTRLIZATION.

AT 2125 A CALL ABOUT A HAZARDOUS DAMAGE AT PD 3 IN BAY #130 WAS MADE TO THE DMP AREA.  J DUNSON RESPONDED TO THE CALL WITH THE SPILL CART.  THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP AREA.  NO LEAKAGE NEEDED TO BE CLEANED UP AND REMOVED FROM THE FLOOR.  THE CONTAMINATED PORTION OF THE DAMAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.  THE SCBA WAS NOT USED BECAUSE THERE NO STRONG ODOR AND/OR FUMES PRESENT.  NO INJURIES OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS DAMAGE.

STEVE AGREED PACKAGE NOT TO BE DELIVERED UNTIL CHECKED BY A FIRST RESPONDER. PACKAGE CAR RETURNED TO THE CENTER, KEYS REMOVED AND CAR SECLUDED ON UPS PROPERTY.  THE VAPORS WERE RELEASED AT THE TIME OF THE INSPECTION BY 1ST RESPONDER, JIM TREMBLY. PER THE DECISION TREE: WERE TO CALL FIRE DEPARTMENT UNABLE TO CLEAN UP PACKAGE.  OPTEK ENVIRONMENTAL CALLED IN; CONTAINERIZED PACKAGE, LEFT ON PROPERTY FOR LATER DISPOSAL.
